\c 10
\p
\v 1 And the queen of Sheba heard the report\f + \fr 10.1: \ft What is the report? In the context the wisdom of Solomon seems to be the primary focus.\f* about Solomon regarding the name of Yhwh,\f + \fr 10.1: \ft How is Yhwh's name involved here? This suggests a positive evaluation of Solomon.\f* and she came to test him with enigmatic questions.
\v 2 And she came to Jerusalem with very great strength,\f + \fr 10.2: \ft ESV: "retinue."\f* camels bearing perfumes and a great deal of gold and precious stone, and she came to Solomon and spoke to him all that was in her heart.
\v 3 And Solomon made known to her all her words\f + \fr 10.3: \ft This is a curiously bland expression. Does it mean he "answered all her questions" (so ESV/NRSV)? Does it mean he spoke on every matter that she raised?\f*; there was no matter hidden\f + \fr 10.3: \ft Niph., Part., msa, עלם.\f* from the king that he did not make known to her.
\v 4 And the queen of Sheba saw all the wisdom of Solomon and the house that he built
\v 5 and the food of his table and the seeting of his servants and the attendance of those waiting on him\f + \fr 10.5: \ft Piel, Part., mp, construct, + 3ms suffix.\f* and their garments and his cup-bearers and his burnt offering that he offered in the house of Yhwh, and there was no longer breath in her! Happy are these your servants, who stand before you continually hearing your wisdom!
\v 9 May Yhwh your God be praised who has delighted\f + \fr 10.9: \ft Interesting choice of verbs. Check for other royal references using this verb.\f* in you to set you on the throne of Israel on account of the love of Yhwh for Israel forever and he placed you as king to do justice and righteousness!"
\v 10 And she gave to the king 120 talents of gold and a great deal of perfume and precious stone. Never again\f + \fr 10.10: \ft This is an important note in the narrative. This is the high point of Solomon's international connections.\f* came like that perfume in such abundance as the queen of Sheba gave to King Solomon.
\p
\v 11 Now\f + \fr 10.11: \ft This paragraph is an offline aside from within the queen of Sheba narrative.\f* also the fleet of Hiram, which brought gold from Ophir, brought from Ophir a great deal of almug wood and precious stone.
\v 12 And the king made almug wood railings\f + \fr 10.12: \ft Meaning uncertain. See Holladay 204.\f* for the house of Yhwh and for the house of the king, and lyres and harps for the singers. Not like that has almug wood come or been seen until this day.\f + \fr 10.12: \ft Yet another hint that this is the high point for Solomon and Israel.\f*
\p
\v 13 And King Solomon gave to the queen of Sheba all she desired which she asked aside from what he had given to her according to the hand of King Solomon.\f + \fr 10.13: \ft To what is this referring?\f* And she turned and went to her land, she and her servants.
\p
\v 14 And the weight of the gold that came to Solomon in one year was six hundred and sixty-six\f + \fr 10.14: \ft Check commentaries for whether scholars link this verse to the use of this number in Revelation.\f* talents of gold,
\v 15 apart from the men of exploring\f + \fr 10.15: \ft ESV: "explorers."\f* and from the ?\f + \fr 10.15: \ft ESV: "business," but Holladay 203 uncertain.\f* of the merchants and all the kings of Arabia and the governors of the land.
\v 16 And King Solomon made two hundred shield of alloyed gold,\f + \fr 10.16: \ft What is the significance of shields?\f* six hundred gold covered each shield.
\v 17 And three hundred shield of alloyed gold; three minas of gold covered each shield, and the king put them in the House of the Forest of Lebanon.\f + \fr 10.17: \ft What is this?\f*
\v 18 And the king made a great throne of ivory, and he overlaid it with pure gold.
\v 19 There were six steps on the throne, and a round top was on the throne from behind, and the hands from this and from this to the place of sitting and two lions standing next to the side.
